<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1437817" src="https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/map-of-Kaduna-state.jpg?resize=440%2C318&#038;ssl=1" alt="Kaduna" width="440" height="318" srcset="https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/map-of-Kaduna-state.jpg?w=440&amp;ssl=1 440w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/map-of-Kaduna-state.jpg?resize=300%2C217&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/map-of-Kaduna-state.jpg?resize=58%2C42&amp;ssl=1 58w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/map-of-Kaduna-state.jpg?resize=260%2C188&amp;ssl=1 260w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/map-of-Kaduna-state.jpg?resize=180%2C130&amp;ssl=1 180w" sizes="(max-width: 440px) 100vw, 440px" data-recalc-dims="1" /> The maiden 2020 Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV) challenge was held on Wednesday at the Jaji military cantonment, Kaduna, to display innovations of Nigerian youths in flying locally made prototype aircraft. The challenge, which showcased locally made aircraft flown by the participants, grouped into three, was mainly to uncover hidden talents. The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reports that the competition was held in collaboration with the Defence Research and Development Bureau, Defence Headquarters, and funded by the Tertiary Education Trust Fund (TETFUND), alongside the Nigerian Communications Commission (NCC) and the National Information Technology Development Agency (NITDA), among others. Speaking at the opening ceremony of the competition, the Chairman, Local Organizing Committee, on the 2020 UAV challenge, Prof. Abiodun Musa, said the applicants went through three stages of screening before 18 participants nationwide were shortlisted for the competition. He explained that the stages included an online application for the competition, screening of the applications by a team of assessors before the 18 participants scaled to the fourth stage to start the competition. “We are trying to get the best of Nigeria who would get the technology to the next level; we made series of advertisements and created a website for Nigerians, who have knowledge of the field, to apply. ”This competition is not only about talent hunt, we also want to have Nigerians who, but we can also train to have the necessary skills for UAV development and deployment in Nigeria. “We are talking about industry 4.0, the key areas to develop are artificial intelligence, UAV and unmanned ground vehicles”, he said. He noted that UAV and other similar technological innovations and expertise would go along way in boosting the desired outcomes for the communication and digital economy sector in the country. “UAVs will also go along way in improving health, disaster management and rescue; the UAV has a very wide area for which it can be used. “The UAV can be used in deliveries by online markets and payments made on board upon arrival, it has come to stay and can be used in many other areas of human endeavour not only for security”, but Musa also said. NAN reports that the winner of the competition would take home N6millon, while the second and third runners-up will receive N3millon  and N2 million, respectively, at the end of the competition on Dec. 10. Vanguard News Nigeria The Nigerian Air Force (NAF) in its resolve to promote innovation and enhance its Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance (ISR) capabilities, Thursday, inducted its first indigenous operational Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV) nicknamed, Tsaigumi. The Tsaigumi UAV, which was produced by NAF Aerospace Engineers in collaboration with UAVision of Portugal, would be… February 15, 2018 In "News" ABUJA— President Goodluck Jonathan, yesterday, unveiled the first indigenous unmanned aerial vehicle, UAV, named GULMA, built by the Nigerian Air Force in Kaduna. December 18, 2013 In "News" President Goodluck Jonathan on Tuesday in Kaduna unveiled the country’s first indigenous unmanned aerial vehicle, GULMA, designed and constructed by the Nigerian Air Force. December 17, 2013 In "News"